Tut, our Horſes they ſhall not ſee, I'le tye them in the wood;
our Vizards we will change after we leave them: and, Sarrah, I have
Caſes of Buckram for the nonce, to immask our noted outward Garments.

Come my Maſters, let us ſhare, and then to Horſe before day;
and the Prince and Poynes be not two arrand Cowards, there's no equity
ſtirring. There's no more Valour in that Poynes, than in a wild Duck.

